Overview

This lab is dedicated to raster analysis and raster-vector interactions.

In our previous lectures, We emphasized attribute operations, spatial operations, and geometric operations primarily using vector data. The same concepts and operations also apply to raster data. Given the expectation that you have mastered the materials for vector data, you should be able to self-study Section 4.3. Spatial operations on raster data, Section 5.3. Geometric operations on raster data, and Chapter 6. Raster-vector interactions and learn how the concepts and operations can be applied to raster data and how both data types can be used interactively.

After you have gone through Section 4.3, Section 5.3, and Chapter 6, explore the following interesting questions.

Don’t forget to comment your code while answering the questions below.

Environment Setup

Load up all libraries needed for this lab.

library(sf)
library(terra)
library(dplyr)
library(spData)

Some of the following exercises use a vector (zion_points) and raster dataset (srtm) from the spDataLarge package. They also use a polygonal ‘convex hull’ derived from the vector dataset (ch) to represent the area of interest.

zion_points_path = system.file("vector/zion_points.gpkg", package = "spDataLarge")
zion_points = read_sf(zion_points_path)
srtm = rast(system.file("raster/srtm.tif", package = "spDataLarge"))
ch = st_combine(zion_points) |>
  st_convex_hull() |> 
  st_as_sf()

# Plot the data to understand their geography
plot(srtm)
plot(zion_points, add =TRUE)
plot(ch, add = TRUE)

Q5. Use the Landsat image provided by the spDataLarge package: rast(system.file(“raster/landsat.tif”, package = “spDataLarge”)) to calculate the Normalized Difference Water Index (NDWI; (green - nir)/(green + nir)) of the image. NDWI is similar to NDVI (see Section 4.3.3) except that NDVI is to enhance the appearance of vegetation from a multispectral image whereas NDWI is to enhance the appearance of water.

Hint: For NDVI and NDWI calculation, please follow the procedure described in Section 4.3.3 of Chapter 4. As described in Chapter 4, the image (which is a Landsat level-2 product) has four spectral bands from the Landsat 8 satellite — blue (band 1 in the image), green (band 2), red (band 3), and near-infrared (NIR, band 4). The Landsat level-2 products are stored as integers to save disk space, and thus we need to convert them to floating-point numbers before doing any calculations. For that purpose, we need to apply a scaling factor (0.0000275) and add an offset (-0.2) to the original values

Bonus: 1 point. Calculate a correlation between NDVI and NDWI for this area. You can use the layerCor() function, and refer to Section 3.3.1 in Chapter 3 for stacking multilayered rasters.
